o deal with this big amount of MAC. And the principles are you just remove enough MAC so that you can put in a good-sized valve safely. And sometimes that requires a very complicated reconstruction. But in this case, the MAC was sufficiently superficial so I could cut it back, as you can see here with these curved scissors, and still have a reasonable annulus, reasonable, again, in parentheses, to sew to. When it's not like this, when it's harder, I've made some tapes about enveloping the whole posterior annulus in bovine pericardium or Dacron. But here, as it turns out, I could take out the posterior leaflet and then use these shark-tooth graspers that are made for orthopedic surgery to grapple off a little more calcium. And if you're going to get involved in doing operations like this, I strongly advise you to try the orthopedic shark-tooth grasper. However, it's bigger than a standard rongure and has teeth. And it allows you to peel off calcium without damaging the annulus. The little shark teeth help with that. And the purpose is not to remove all the calcium. It's just to remove it back to where it's manageable. And by manageable, I mean you can either put pledgeded sutures underneath it, which is what I ended up doing here, just like a normal mitral valve replacement. Or alternatively, enveloping the whole posterior annulus in the material I just mentioned. And if you want to learn about that, you'll have to see another video because we're going to concentrate on this one on doing just a standard mitral valve replacement through an odd surgical approach, but one that's very effective. And so this is P2. I always start right in the middle of P2 and then run up each side. And it usually takes eight or nine sutures to envelop the basically posterior two-thirds of what will end up being an enlarged mitral annulus because we're going to put a patch where that hole is now in the aortic continuity. And that patch will enlarge both the mitral annulus and the aortic an