'll just sew it up and then come into the outside here and leave it on the outside. And we're going to use this whole patch to close the aorta. We won't just use part of it, and you close the aorta to aorta anywhere. And now we're doing the same thing on the other side. Notice that on this side, instead of coming up to the graft, through the graft, we're coming up through the patient's aorta. And the reason for that is we want to sew this forehand just exactly the way we sewed the other one forehand. So we're always sewing forehand and toward our nose. This is one of my mantras, you know, make it easy for yourself. Sew forehand and toward yourself whenever you can, because that's the way you go the quickest. And so now we just line up this and keep sewing up the side. And another thing to notice here while we're sewing this is that triangular graft isn't straight across. There's actually an outward curve to it so that it will accept. Watch when this sizer goes in. You can see how the graft is sufficiently large to bow out when a prosthesis is implanted. So it becomes part of the circumference of the patient's annulus rather than a secant. And now we'll complete the aortic annular suture line. Remember, we put the first eight or so sutures in early in the case when we could clearly identify the aortic annulus. And now that the patch is in place that completes the cylindrical aorta, we can place the remaining four or five sutures, usually four, along that patch. And the ones that cross the aortic suture line there will squash that suture line between the prosthesis annulus inside and the pledging outside. Also notice that the aortic suture line is cleanly above the mitral suture line, just like it is in life. So here is the last of these sutures that crosses the aortic suture line on the other side and must seal that suture line between the prosthesis on the inside and the pledging on the outside. And in addition, it has to line up perfectly with the previous sutures 