shed it in. The next step is to close the aorta completely. And since we put that black line in the middle, we can now line that up with the foreshad of the aortotomy there on the assistant side of the table on the left. Cut it to length. It shouldn't be pulled tight. It should just be gently brought across because the corrugations in the graft will allow you to set it nicely. So yorking it out straight won't help you. And then you'll notice that I double bite this. And the reason I do that is I want that graft to land inside the aorta. It's all on the inside of the aorta from the part we've already done because we were sowing from inside the aorta. But now we're sowing from outside the aorta. So in order to get it to sit inside, we have to double bite the graft until the graft realizes that it wants to be inside. And the reason we want it inside is it bleeds less when the corrugations are in. And second, you get a much better bearing surface of the graft on the patient's aorta when you double bite because there's a bigger hunk of aortic graft sitting on the patient's aorta. And then I use a 3-O-proline to do this. I know some people use lighter material, but I like the 3-O-proline. I'm not trying to find out how delicate I am. I'm trying to get the job done without breaking a suture. And if I run into some calcium, the heavier suture can be of help. And now notice we're also going to sew forehand and towards ourselves this way, except instead of going from graft to aorta, we're going to be sowing from aorta to graft so that we continue to double bite to leave the graft inside the patient's aorta like you see right there. And then it's just a matter of sewing the thing together. You can see the graft is already beginning to realize that it wants to sit inside because we've bent it over a little bit. It's just a few millimeters, but it makes a big difference in how dry it is. Although I must tell you that many of these, I'll run a little Cryolife BioGlue along the si